### Alternative Approach: Builder Pattern

If you prefer not to deal with error handling in every migration creation, you could use a builder pattern:

```go
// BaseMigrationBuilder builds a validated BaseMigration
type BaseMigrationBuilder struct {
	name        string
	version     int
	description string
	err         error
}

// NewBaseMigrationBuilder creates a new builder
func NewBaseMigrationBuilder() *BaseMigrationBuilder {
	return &BaseMigrationBuilder{}
}

// WithName sets the migration name
func (b *BaseMigrationBuilder) WithName(name string) *BaseMigrationBuilder {
	if name == "" {
		b.err = errors.New("migration name cannot be empty")
	}
	b.name = name
	return b
}

// WithVersion sets the migration version
func (b *BaseMigrationBuilder) WithVersion(version int) *BaseMigrationBuilder {
	if version < 1 {
		b.err = errors.New("migration version must be greater than 0")
	}
	b.version = version
	return b
}

// WithDescription sets the migration description
func (b *BaseMigrationBuilder) WithDescription(description string) *BaseMigrationBuilder {
	b.description = description
	return b
}

// Build creates a new BaseMigration or returns an error
func (b *BaseMigrationBuilder) Build() (BaseMigration, error) {
	if b.err != nil {
		return BaseMigration{}, b.err
	}

	if b.name == "" {
		return BaseMigration{}, errors.New("migration name is required")
	}

	if b.version < 1 {
		return BaseMigration{}, errors.New("migration version is required and must be > 0")
	}

	return BaseMigration{
		name:        b.name,
		version:     b.version,
		description: b.description,
	}, nil
}
```

### Recommendation

The first approach (using unexported fields with validation in `NewBaseMigration`) is simpler and more straightforward. It enforces validation while keeping the API clean and easy to use.

This approach allows you to add proper validation while ensuring it can't be bypassed, maintaining integrity in your migration system.


